    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-01-25T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-01-25T12:00:00-05:00" n="851"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d851">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">612.006/1–2446: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Messersmith</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-01-25T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 25, 1946—noon.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>72. <gloss target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 54, Jan 22.<note n="20"
                        xml:id="d851fn20">Not printed; in it the Ambassador reported that the
                        Mexican Under Secretary of the Treasury promised to discuss the entire
                        question of import controls with Embassy representatives beginning the
                        following Monday morning (612.006/1–2246).</note> Ref projected import
                    control discussions Mon. Dept recognizes fully excellent efforts of <gloss
                        target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> but believes time has come for strongest formal
                    representations to Mex Govt, particularly in view flood protests by affected
                    U.S. interests.</p>
                <p>Unless objection is perceived, therefore, formal note in strong terms should be
                    prepared for presentation on Mon by Ambassador to <gloss target="#t_MinFonAff1"
                        >MinFonAff</gloss>. Copy could also be used by other <gloss target="#t_Emb1"
                        >Emb</gloss> officers in projected discussions with other officials. Note
                    should refer to specific provisions trade agreement, assurances given with
                    respect to operation of controls, manner in which they have apparently not been
                    carried out, US Govt expectation of firm statement by Mex Govt confirming
                    intention to fulfill its international obligations under trade agreement,
                    followed by action to that end. If <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> desires,
                    draft text could be discussed with Dept by telephone.</p>
                <p>Moreover, unless <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> perceives serious objection,
                    Dept proposes to have high officer call on Mex Ambassador in near future to
                    present strong note in similar terms as means of reinforcing <gloss
                        target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss>’s efforts. Your reaction to this proposal
                    requested urgently.<note n="21" xml:id="d851fn21">In despatch 28,194, January
                        29, 1946, Ambassador Messersmith expressed his opinion that “no useful
                        purpose would be served by making a formal protest at this time” and that by
                        conversations with the Mexican officials they could secure elimination from
                        the Treasury lists of most of the articles therein.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
